&gt; 
&gt; The JUnit TestRunner is, by default, in loading mode. That is, modified
&gt; classes are reloaded, when runnning the test. 
&gt; This causes problems when using EJBs in the test cases. A
&gt; ClassCastException occurs with the EJB implementation. Different
&gt; classloaders are used for the EJB in the test case and the EJB in the
&gt; application server. To overcome this problem, disable the loading property
&gt; in the junit.properties file.
&gt; 
&gt; Add a junit.properties file for preference settings. It is stored in the
&gt; folder referred to by the &quot;user.home&quot; property. The supported setting is
&gt; loading, it can be set to true or false to enable or disable the loading
&gt; behavior. 
&gt; 
&gt; On Windows 2000, &quot;user.home&quot; could be C:&#92;Documents and Settings&#92;user 
&gt; A drawback to disabling the loading behavior, is that modified test cases
&gt; will require JUnit to be restarted. 
&gt; 
&gt; Find attached a sample junit.properties file. 
